04569nam a22006495i 9780271091495DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780271091495  a(DE-B1597)617614  a(OCoLC)1291506605  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aR141b.B66 2022 7aART0150702bisacsh04a610.942231 aBorland, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVisualizing Household Health :bMedieval Women, Art, and Knowledge in the Régime du corps /cJennifer Borland. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b33 color/52 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Visual Language of the Régime du corps -- t2. The Illustrated Manuscripts and Their Audiences -- t3. The Medical Context for the Régime du corps -- t4. Household Management, Status, and the Care of the Body -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1: Summary of Illustrated Copies -- tAppendix 2: Scenes Depicted in Each Illustrated Copy -- tAppendix 3: Known Manuscript Copies of the Régime du corps -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1256, the countess of Provence, Beatrice of Savoy, enlisted her personal physician to create a health handbook to share with her daughters. Written in French and known as the Régime du corps, this health guide would become popular and influential, with nearly seventy surviving copies made over the next two hundred years and translations in at least four other languages. In Visualizing Household Health, art historian Jennifer Borland uses the Régime to show how gender and health care converged within the medieval household.Visualizing Household Health explores the nature of the households portrayed in the Régime and how their members interacted with professionalized medicine. Borland focuses on several illustrated versions of the manuscript that contain historiated initials depicting simple scenes related to health care, such as patients’ consultations with physicians, procedures like bloodletting, and foods and beverages recommended for good health. Borland argues that these images provide important details about the nature of women’s agency in the home—and offer highly compelling evidence that women enacted multiple types of health care. Additionally, she contends, the Régime opens a window onto the history of medieval women as owners, patrons, and readers of books. Interdisciplinary in scope, this book broadens notions of the medieval medical community and the role of women in medieval health care. It will be welcomed by scholars and students of women’s history, art history, book history, and the history of medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHistoriated initialszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMedical carezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMedicine, MedievalzEurope. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076692940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027109149540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271091495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271091495/original  a978-3-11-076692-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK